The '''Clergy of the Church of England database''' ('''CCEd''') is an online database of [[clergy]] of the [[Church of England]] between 1540 and 1835.
The database project began in 1999 with funding from the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]], and is ongoing as a collaboration between [[King's College London]], the [[University of Kent]] and [[Durham University]]. As of September 2014, the database contained nearly 1.5 million evidential records about the careers of Church of England clergy, and the public version of the database had information on over 155,000 individuals.<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://theclergydatabase.org.uk/about/|website=CCEd: Clergy of the Church of England Database Project|publisher=King's College London|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>
==Notable people== The CCEd has had three joint-directors since 1999: * Professor [[Arthur Burns (historian)|Arthur Burns]], King's College London<ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Arthur Burns|url=https://www.kcl.ac.uk/artshums/depts/history/people/staff/Academic/burnsa/index.aspx|website=Department of History|publisher=King's College London|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> * Professor Kenneth Fincham, University of Kent<ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Kenneth Fincham|url=https://www.kent.ac.uk/history/staff/profiles/fincham.html|website=School of History|publisher=University of Kent|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> * Professor Stephen Taylor, Durham University<ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Stephen Taylor|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/history/staff/profiles/?id=9141|website=Department of History|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>
